{"active_answer": "a half hitch on the loop created by the first half hitch", "active_index": 273, "active_question": "What locks the exit of a slipped half hitch into place?", "audit_index": 9, "decision": "keep", "document_sha256": "3d046eb52babac1a6d3e8d0204d6c67db8a0f1f7daba5698953a4d761833d17d", "fact_id": "fact-a3fb0bf625fecebfa5e0", "projection_lineage": {"active_index": 273, "baseline_rows": 548, "baseline_sha256": "1c585357d18896cdd0264ce0502dfb600a2c2bf76f6c726e3b74b46d4902a8f7", "prior_context_merit_review": false}, "reason": "The answer identifies the specific second hitch that locks the exit of the described quick-release structure.", "reason_code": "quick_release_locking_mechanism", "review_pass": "first_context_merit_review_of_v48_projection_row", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v49", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 12, "bare_answer_points": 0, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 11, "risk_score": 0, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v49", "source": "rope365", "source_document": "data/raw/rope365_c89abf7c3a5c30e1.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "8c9a9ef9bd3d4e4213db040b0bafb5a80cf054cb2e137378d61ebab51b09ba80", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "A slipped half hitch is made by not pulling the rope completely through and tightening the hitch. You’ll need to start from a change of direction or some friction on the hitch’s origin as the entry point will not be locked. Then we make a half hitch on the loop created by the first half hitch to lock the exit into place.", "support_evidence_sha256": "5e2e82a0d1f4ae01ff1edec5835cf9ebe48561607d18af123a2d95391fa20a01", "url": "https://rope365.com/quick-release/"}
{"active_answer": "a technique in its own right that specifically only ever uses one rope", "active_index": 95, "active_question": "How does WykD distinguish Ichinawa from merely practicing with one rope?", "audit_index": 10, "decision": "keep", "document_sha256": "ca4af3374c7b1554a16f969a19a55d3e8acd8ff776f675eaec19b1779ec32511", "fact_id": "fact-fcea3c04b3e8979d1e24", "projection_lineage": {"active_index": 95, "baseline_rows": 548, "baseline_sha256": "1c585357d18896cdd0264ce0502dfb600a2c2bf76f6c726e3b74b46d4902a8f7", "prior_context_merit_review": false}, "reason": "Unlike an isolated translation lookup, the attributed answer explains the author's substantive distinction between a named technique and a one-rope practice constraint.", "reason_code": "explicitly_attributed_ichinawa_technique_distinction", "review_pass": "first_context_merit_review_of_v48_projection_row", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v49", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 13, "bare_answer_points": 0, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 11, "risk_score": 0, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v49", "source": "wykd", "source_document": "data/raw/wykd_a74fec63b0114fff.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "91fc248bcbee1123883003e54d1e0eced40dcedace26cf7f6ac7e3538c0e503f", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "It’s also worth remembering that though plenty advise practising with one rope they would use Ippon for that because they’re specifying the number of ropes to be used, as opposed to the Ichinawa technique which is a technique that does not exist just for practice but as a technique in its own right that specifically only ever uses one rope. And as it only ever uses one rope the name is only for description to distinguish this technique because counting the ropes used is errr…. somewhat redundant given that there will only ever be one.", "support_evidence_sha256": "b76830990aa050717d8b21f33c8d45be540f97ca2e7504ad5902ed53bc1629ee", "url": "https://wykd.com/shibari-kinbaku-bondage-teaching/2012/10/14/ichinawa-ippon-me-no-nawa-and-one-rope/"}
